Gloria Brown was the first African American woman to hold the position of a forest supervisor with the U.S. Forest Service, running the Siuslaw and later the Los Padres National Forests. Throughout her career, Brown was a catalyst for change and a genuine icon in USFS. Brown credited her career to all the relationships made and people met along the way. This article was written in honor of Black History Month 2022. https://foreststewardsguild.org/enews/highlighting-author-and-icon-gloria-brown/

Riverland is currently seeking an unlimited full time position of Building Utilities Mechanic ‚Äì Albert Lea. Application deadline is May 9th, 2022. Application Procedure: Please apply online at https://www.mn.gov/mmb/careers.:=:https://mn.gov/mmb/careers. Search for Job ID 52125. Position Purpose: The employee is responsible for operating, maintaining, and repairing of boilers, control systems, plumbing fixtures and other systems included in the building envelope. Basic understanding of chillers, pumps, cooling towers, pneumatic controls and water treatment. Manages building supply and equipment inventory, and documents all service-related activities (including report writing). May exercise some responsibilities for purchasing materials, work performed by outside vendors and approving bill of ladings/invoices. Work is done in accordance with established procedures and frequent and detailed instructions are given on new and complex work. Under general supervision, performs semi-skilled jobs in a variety of trade areas. Work is usually assigned and inspected by the Physical Plant Supervisor.

Today in #LaborHistory: Construction begins on the Hawks Nest Tunnel for a Union Carbide hydroelectric project. 3,000 mostly African-American migrant workers from the South were hired to complete the project and, to save time and money, were not provided with proper safety equipment to work cutting rock that had been discovered to have a high silica content. The official death toll from silicosis was 476, with estimates as high as 700 to 1,000. It is considered to be one of the worst industrial disasters in U.S. history - 1930.

There's still time to join us for a virtual lunch tour with @tamerlainesanctuary! Secure your spot now with a pay-what-you-can donation: https://www.eventbrite.com/e/virtual-sanctuary-tour-with-tamerlaine-sanctuary-and-preserve-tickets-328147898197:=:https://www.eventbrite.com/e/328147898197 Get ready to meet Tamerlaine's rescued residents up close and personal! Hear the stories of several of their 275+ animals, including how they got there, and who they are as individuals. You'll see each of them as we do: as unique members of the "famerlaine," deserving of love and respect. A virtual visit to Tamerlaine is a joyful experience that will restore your spirit and your faith in a compassionate world. Your pay-what-you-can donation will go directly to PAN and Tamerlaine to help continue to save animals of all species. Tamerlaine Sanctuary and Preserve is located in Montague, NJ. They are proud to be the first sanctuary in New Jersey certified by the Global Federation of Animal Sanctuaries. Located on 336 bucolic acres, they are home to over 275 rescued animals, as well as a nature preserve and dedicated pollinator garden. Their four-part mission consists of caring for abused and neglected farmed animals, conserving their land, educating the public about animal protection and environmental ethics, and advocating for a compassionate society. Ultimately, their goal is to empower people to experience the interconnection we share with all species and the Earth.

With Pilate‚Äôs permission, he came and took the body away. He was accompanied by Nicodemus, the man who earlier had visited Jesus at night. Nicodemus brought a mixture of myrrh and aloes, about seventy-five pounds. Taking Jesus‚Äô body, the two of them wrapped it, with the spices, in strips of linen. This was in accordance with Jewish burial customs. At the place where Jesus was crucified, there was a garden, and in the garden a new tomb, in which no one had ever been laid. The Myrna Loy acknowledges Black History Month with the searing new documentary, "Who We Are," running Feb 11-24. The film emerged when host Jeffrey Robinson began trying to explain the Civil Rights Movement to his young nephew. CW: Discussions of white supremacy, racism, and violence. On the day that thousands of people rallied at #BansOffOurBodies events across the country, a white supremacist murdered 10 Black people in Buffalo, NY. Our country has a long history of subjugation over and violence against Black bodies. There must be demands for accountability, there must be demands for justice, and there must be demands for an end to the inequity that continues to define every moment of Black America. Our mission is to fight for reproductive freedom, which we know is unattainable for Black, Indigenous, and people of color when they are persecuted simply for existing. We also have to acknowledge the painful reality that a lot of people in historically marginalized communities are too busy stressing about everything else that is raining down upon them to turn out to rally for abortion rights. Planned Parenthood is committed to true allyship to BIPOC communities and dismantling white supremacy in all its forms.

One of the many avenues of outreach our amazing Who I Am Foundation volunteers provides is our year round BI-WEEKLY care package distributions to homeless and less fortunate individuals. Our distributions have been our most consistent outreach projects since 2013. Our amazing Volunteers organize and execute the distributions, alternating between a mobile distribution and a stationary distribution. Currently, we are blessed with the ability to assist an average of 1,000 people per month; in multiple cities, in multiple states! Our goal with distributions since 2013, has been to provide essential necessities to those in need. Necessities that we may take for granted, are viewed as a luxury to those without. Some of the items we hand out include food, clothing, bottled waters, hygiene items, first aid supplies, socks, shoes, books, seasonal items, and lists of resources available in the area. We also utilize our time in the community, retrieving feedback of needs and issues, by those in need. Engaging with individuals, learning their stories, and providing them hope. Our distributions continually evolve. Addressing needs, while making available the proper resources. Tangible donations are the lifeblood of our distributions. Your contribution of any of the items below, help to ensure each and every distribution is effective and impactful. Learn how you can help us by donating, or volunteering, by contacting us at any time. www.WhoIAmFoundation.org:=:https://www.whoiamfoundation.org/ #TeamWhoIAm

We are celebrating Black History Month here at the Food Bank of Delaware! Throughout the month we'll celebrate the important contributions that Black Americans have made towards ending hunger and poverty in our country! Shirley Chisholm was the first Black woman in Congress and instrumental in creating the National School Lunch program, expanding the food stamp program (now SNAP), and establishing the Special Supplemental Nutrition Program for Women, Infants and Children, commonly known as WIC.

Marine Private First Class William B. Baugh is one of only three Ohioans who earned the Medal of Honor for their heroic actions during the Korean War. At the age of 18, Baugh left his job working in a shoe factory in Harrison, Ohio, to enlist in the U.S. Marine Corps. Two years later in Korea, during a night-time raid on Nov. 29, 1950, a grenade landed inside the vehicle in which he and his comrades were traveling. Baugh used his body to absorb the explosion of the grenade, saving his fellow soldiers‚Äô lives at the cost of his own. For his superb courage and valiant spirit of self-sacrifice, Baugh was posthumously awarded the Medal of Honor. William Baugh was inducted in to the Ohio Veterans Hall of Fame in 1999. #MedalOfHonorMonth #Gratitude #Ohiovets #OhioFindItHere

A new study reports that nearly one in 10 people from ethnic minority groups who refused a COVID-19 vaccine report experiencing racial discrimination in a medical setting during the pandemic and twice as many incidents of discrimination as those who volunteered to receive the vaccine. While this study took place in the United Kingdom, experts say it‚Äôs likely these dynamics persist as a reason for vaccine hesitancy among people of color in the United States. Because the issue of racism in healthcare is systemic, only systemic solutions are likely to be sufficient to solve the problem, experts say. Some approaches include working with the local community and faith-based organizations and minority leaders to improve trust before rolling out a vaccination program. . . . #blackhealth #blackhealthmatters #africanamerican #BlackBodyHealth #CenterForBlackHealthAndEquity #CenterForBlackHealth #PublicHealthMatters #BlackNews #HealthNews #HealthEquity #Equity #PublicHealth #HealthEquity #HealthDisparities #Healthcare #HealthyBlackMen #HealthyBlackWomen #Nonprofits #HealthJustice #COVID19 #Vaccine #Pfizer #Vaxx #mRNA #CDC #Covid

Myra Adele Logan First woman to perform open-heart surgery In 1943, Dr. Myra Adele Logan became the first woman to perform open-heart surgery. It was reportedly the ninth time the procedure had been performed worldwide. Logan‚Äôs research included studying antibiotics and breast cancer. Her notable contributions include developing more accurate tests to detect density differences in breast tissue. A surgeon at Harlem Hospital in New York, she was also a founding partner of the first physicians group practice in the United States.

On May 8, 1945 - known as Victory in Europe Day or V-E Day - celebrations erupted around the world to mark the end of World War II in Europe. By the beginning of 1945, the German army had been weakened and defeat looked likely. Tuesday 8 May, 1945, was an emotional day that millions of people had been waiting for. Many people were extremely happy that the fighting had stopped and there were big celebrations and street parties. Huge crowds - with lots of people dressed in red, white and blue - gathered outside Buckingham Palace in London. They cheered as King George VI and his family, including Princess Elizabeth (the current queen) and Princess Margaret, came out onto the balcony to greet everybody. Princess Elizabeth and her sister were allowed to leave the palace and celebrate with crowds outside, although they had to do it secretly. The future Queen described it as "one of the most memorable nights of my life". But VE Day was also a moment of great sadness and reflection, as millions of people had lost their lives or loved ones in the conflict. Many had to continue fighting in other battles and lots of people were being kept as prisoners of war abroad. "Our rejoicing is sobered and subdued by a supreme consciousness of the terrible price we have paid to rid the world of Hitler and his evil band. Let us not forget, my fellow Americans, the sorrow and the heartache, which today abide in the homes of so many of our neighbors - neighbors whose most priceless possession has been rendered as a sacrifice to redeem our liberty." President Harry S. Truman ‚ù§Ô∏èüá∫üá∏

It was at Howard University where #PauliMurray developed one of their most influential and prescient theories #JaneCrow. As a gender fluid person, Pauli became increasingly aware of the conjunction of racism and sexism in their own life, and in the lives of Black women, Murray used the expression #JaneCrow ‚Äî alluding to ‚ÄúJim Crow,‚Äù the discriminatory system of state and local laws that enforced racial segregation in the southern United States ‚Äî to articulate how racial and gender-based oppressions combined to circumscribe Black women‚Äôs freedom, a theory that would later become known as #intersectionality. It is at the intersection of race and gender where YWCAs across the country meet to do the work to #eliminateracism, #empowerwomen, and create a world of peace, justice, freedom, and dignity for all. #BlackHistoryMonth #EliminatingRacism #ywcaisonamission #YWCAKzoo ID: A black and white photo of Pauli Murray wearing glasses & writing.
